 :tx/rationale "ASSESSMENT FINDING: Drift Component Φ Linear Scaling Problem — bilateral.rs line 1144-1145, trilateral.rs lines 192-220. Divergence Φ counts total boundary gaps but does not weight by severity or coverage quality. A spec with falsification but no impl counts the same as a spec with neither. D = 1 - Φ/Φ_max is linear, where Φ_max = entity_count. As the project grows (more entities → larger Φ_max), marginal improvements from closing individual gaps have diminishing returns on D. Closing 10 gaps when Φ_max=100 gives ΔD=+0.10. Closing 10 gaps when Φ_max=1000 gives ΔD=+0.01. This creates a structural bias against convergence in large stores — the larger the store grows, the harder it is for gap closure to move F(S). FIX options: (1) Weight gaps by formality level (unfalsifiable spec gap counts less than well-specified gap). (2) Use log-scale for Φ: D = 1 - log(Φ+1)/log(Φ_max+1). (3) Normalize by current-stage entities only (exclude Phase E specs from Phase B denominator). Option 3 is most principled — only measure convergence against what should be converged at the current phase. VERIFICATION: Compare D component across sessions with linear vs log vs phase-scoped formulas. Phase-scoped should show movement where linear shows stagnation. INTERACTS WITH: F(S) stagnation (D is 0.18 weight), structural ceiling risk (D's linear scaling may be a contributor), verification sprint (gap closure impact depends on Φ_max). TRACES TO: INV-BILATERAL-003 (F(S) component semantics), ADR-FOUNDATION-014."
